# Critical extraction note: hibp_search uses **CLI11
# `->check(CLI::Range(...))` chained validator
# pattern** at hibp_search.cpp:58 — `app.add_option(
# "--toc-bits", cli.toc_bits, ...)->check(CLI::
# Range(15, 25))`.  CLI11's add_option returns an
# `Option*` pointer; method-chain `->check(...)`
# attaches a VALIDATOR OBJECT to the option.
# CLI11 ships built-in validators: `CLI::Range(MIN,
# MAX)` (inclusive integer range), `CLI::ExistingFile`,
# `CLI::ExistingDirectory`, `CLI::NonexistentPath`,
# `CLI::PositiveNumber`, `CLI::IsMember(set)`, plus
# any callable `[](auto& v){...}` lambda.
# Validators run BEFORE the value reaches the
# bound reference — rejection is caught by
# CLI11_PARSE's macro-injected try/catch.  Distinct
# from R304 Ada (no equivalent; caller validates
# post-Getopt), R301 Nim cligen (validates via Nim
# type coercion at parseInt time), R302 Clojure
# babashka.cli (no built-in validators — caller
# checks the map).  Closest analog: argparse
# `type=int, choices=range(15, 26)`.  Corpus's
# **first documented chainable-method-validator
# CLI pattern**.
